  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1356106801" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1356106801" />
    <a title="Bianca" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29843800-bianca"><img alt="Bianca" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589154116p2/29843800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1356106801?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bianca" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bianca" href="/user/show/29843800-bianca">Bianca</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=netgalley">netgalley</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=arc">arc</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=female-author">female-author</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=alternate-povs">alternate-povs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29843800-bianca?shelf=3rd-person-narrative">3rd-person-narrative</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1356106801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5081974201843366191">This was my first Alice Hoffman novel. And what a tremendous novel this was. I must say, when I first saw the cover, I instantly thought of Gabriel Garcia Marquez and Isabel Allende, probably because the model looks South American. And true enough, the tone and the mystical aspects of the novel gave it a Marquez-esque and Allende-esque flavour. I wonder if others thought the same.<br/><br/>While I&apos;m not the biggest fan of historical fiction, especially when it&apos;s got fictionalised actual historical figures</span>
  <span id="freeText5081974201843366191" style="display:none">This was my first Alice Hoffman novel. And what a tremendous novel this was. I must say, when I first saw the cover, I instantly thought of Gabriel Garcia Marquez and Isabel Allende, probably because the model looks South American. And true enough, the tone and the mystical aspects of the novel gave it a Marquez-esque and Allende-esque flavour. I wonder if others thought the same.<br /><br />While I'm not the biggest fan of historical fiction, especially when it's got fictionalised actual historical figures, I thoroughly enjoyed <i>the Marriage of Opposites</i> as there were so many things I appreciated.Where do I start?<br /><br />Hoffman has a beautiful writing style, I thought her description of St. Thomas was fantastic, I could almost feel, smell and taste the place. <br /><br />The novel is mostly about Rachel Pomie Pizzaro’s life, the mum of the impressionist painter, Camille Pissarro. Rachel is a force to be reckoned with. She’s feisty, intelligent, outspoken and very stubborn. She dreams of escaping to Paris. She questions her place in the world, she questions why she has to obey silly rules, why women have no rights. Unfortunately, when her father’s business is failing, she feels obligated to marry a man much older, who already had three children. So she becomes Rachel Pomie. She adores her new husband’s children and has four more with him. But by the age of twenty-nine, she’s a widow with seven children. According to the rules of the times, all her family’s possessions will be passed onto a nephew of her husband’s, who is to arrive from Paris and take over the estate. And that is Frederik Pizzarro, who’s just a young twenty-two years old man from Paris. He falls in love/lust with Rachel the moment he sets eyes on her. He’s a pious, hardworking, intelligent and principled man. Rachel finally has a chance at love. Rachel and Frederik’s love has to overcome lots of obstacles imposed by their culture and the times. <br /><br />There are quite a few characters in this novel, some get more “air time” than others. One of the more prominent characters is Jestine, Rachel’s best friend. Her story is full of love and heartbreak, but happiness finds her later in her life.<br /><br />It’s worth mentioning the unique structure of the novel, which is made up of eleven chapters, five of those consisting of Rachel’s narration in the first person. When we get to meet Rachel's second husband, Abraham Gabriel Frederick Pizzarro, Hoffman switches to the third person narrative. Three chapters are dedicated to Jacobo Camille Pizzarro, Rachel and Frederick’s youngest son. I thought the author’s use of the first person narrative in one of those chapters and then the third person narration for the other two chapters was quite unusual. I can’t say it bothered me, although it’d probably have made more sense to just stick with the third person narration when it came to Camille Pissarro, but what do I know? I just don’t recall ever encountering this type of leaping between first and third person narratives within one novel, which it doesn’t mean it’s not a viable novel structure.<br /><br />I appreciated that the author gave us some background history on how the Jewish people came to live on that remote, tropical island. I like learning something new when I read. <br /><br />I thought the first part of the novel, which was mostly about Rachel, was better, as it was more layered. The last two-three chapters felt a bit rushed and crammed, but it seems to me that’s the norm with most novels these days, as the authors seem to rush to the resolution.<br /> <br />Regardless, this was a beautiful, lyrical novel. It is a novel about love, and family, and responsibilities; it’s about women’s rights or, better said, lack of rights; it’s about Jewish traditions and customs; it’s about the power of friendship; it’s about secrets and loss, and moving on. It’s about the agony and, occasionally, the ecstasy of life. <br /><br /><b>4-4.5 stars</b><br /><br /><i>I've received this novel via NetGalley in exchange for an honest review. Many thanks to Simon &amp; Schuster for the opportunity to read and review.</i><br />PS:<b> If you're not familiar with Camille Pissarro's works, look him up. He was amazing!!! Here's a link: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.camillepissarro.org/camille-pissarro-painting-gallery1.jsp">http://www.camillepissarro.org/camill...</a># </b><br /><br /><b>Cover:</b> 4+ stars</span>
  <a data-text-id="5081974201843366191" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


